## Usage

The default variant includes `cmake`, `gcc`, `g++`, `make`, `ninja`, and the GNU C Library development headers. The `-builder` variants additionally include `gdb`.

### Using a Multi-stage Build

For production-ready images, use a multi-stage build. Configure and build with CMake in the build stage, then copy the resulting binary to a minimal runtime image.

```dockerfile
# Build stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/cmake:latest AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN cmake -B build -G Ninja && cmake --build build

# Runtime stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/core-runtime:latest
COPY --from=builder /app/build/myapp /usr/bin/myapp
ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/bin/myapp"]
```

### Using Builder Variants

The `-builder` variants include the `dnf` package manager and additional tools such as `gdb`. Use these variants if the application requires additional packages or debugging tools during the build stage.

```dockerfile
# Build stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/cmake:latest-builder AS builder
RUN dnf install -y <packages> && dnf clean all
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN cmake -B build && cmake --build build

# Runtime stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/core-runtime:latest
COPY --from=builder /app/build/myapp /usr/bin/myapp
ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/bin/myapp"]
```

